#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:327
msgid "profiling test duration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:333
msgid ""
"If you have a slow running large test suite you might want to find out which "
"tests are the slowest. Let's make an artificial test suite:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:336
msgid ""
"# content of test_some_are_slow.py\n"
"\n"
"import time\n"
"\n"
"def test_funcfast():\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"def test_funcslow1():\n"
"    time.sleep(0.1)\n"
"\n"
"def test_funcslow2():\n"
"    time.sleep(0.2)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:351
msgid "Now we can profile which test functions execute the slowest::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:353
msgid ""
"$ py.test --durations=3\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 3 items\n"
"\n"
"test_some_are_slow.py ...\n"
"\n"
"======= slowest 3 test durations ========\n"
"0.20s call     test_some_are_slow.py::test_funcslow2\n"
"0.10s call     test_some_are_slow.py::test_funcslow1\n"
"0.00s teardown test_some_are_slow.py::test_funcslow2\n"
"======= 3 passed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:368
msgid "incremental testing - test steps"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:372
msgid ""
"Sometimes you may have a testing situation which consists of a series of "
"test steps.  If one step fails it makes no sense to execute further steps as "
"they are all expected to fail anyway and their tracebacks add no insight.  "
"Here is a simple ``conftest.py`` file which introduces an ``incremental`` "
"marker which is to be used on classes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:378
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_runtest_makereport(item, call):\n"
"    if \"incremental\" in item.keywords:\n"
"        if call.excinfo is not None:\n"
"            parent = item.parent\n"
"            parent._previousfailed = item\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_runtest_setup(item):\n"
"    if \"incremental\" in item.keywords:\n"
"        previousfailed = getattr(item.parent, \"_previousfailed\", None)\n"
"        if previousfailed is not None:\n"
"            pytest.xfail(\"previous test failed (%s)\" %previousfailed.name)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:396
msgid ""
"These two hook implementations work together to abort incremental-marked "
"tests in a class.  Here is a test module example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:399
msgid ""
"# content of test_step.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.incremental\n"
"class TestUserHandling:\n"
"    def test_login(self):\n"
"        pass\n"
"    def test_modification(self):\n"
"        assert 0\n"
"    def test_deletion(self):\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"def test_normal():\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:417
msgid "If we run this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:419
msgid ""
"$ py.test -rx\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_step.py .Fx.\n"
"======= short test summary info ========\n"
"XFAIL test_step.py::TestUserHandling::()::test_deletion\n"
"  reason: previous test failed (test_modification)\n"
"\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ TestUserHandling.test_modification ________\n"
"\n"
"self = <test_step.TestUserHandling object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_modification(self):\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_step.py:9: AssertionError\n"
"======= 1 failed, 2 passed, 1 xfailed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:442
msgid ""
"We'll see that ``test_deletion`` was not executed because "
"``test_modification`` failed.  It is reported as an \"expected failure\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:447
msgid "Package/Directory-level fixtures (setups)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:449
msgid ""
"If you have nested test directories, you can have per-directory fixture "
"scopes by placing fixture functions in a ``conftest.py`` file in that "
"directory You can use all types of fixtures including :ref:`autouse fixtures "
"<autouse fixtures>` which are the equivalent of xUnit's setup/teardown "
"concept.  It's however recommended to have explicit fixture references in "
"your tests or test classes rather than relying on implicitly executing setup/"
"teardown functions, especially if they are far away from the actual tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:457
msgid ""
"Here is a an example for making a ``db`` fixture available in a directory:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:459
msgid ""
"# content of a/conftest.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"class DB:\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"session\")\n"
"def db():\n"
"    return DB()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:471
msgid "and then a test module in that directory:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:473
msgid ""
"# content of a/test_db.py\n"
"def test_a1(db):\n"
"    assert 0, db  # to show value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:479
msgid "another test module:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:481
msgid ""
"# content of a/test_db2.py\n"
"def test_a2(db):\n"
"    assert 0, db  # to show value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:487
msgid ""
"and then a module in a sister directory which will not see the ``db`` "
"fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:490
msgid ""
"# content of b/test_error.py\n"
"def test_root(db):  # no db here, will error out\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:496
msgid "We can run this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:498
msgid ""
"$ py.test\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 7 items\n"
"\n"
"test_step.py .Fx.\n"
"a/test_db.py F\n"
"a/test_db2.py F\n"
"b/test_error.py E\n"
"\n"
"======= ERRORS ========\n"
"_______ ERROR at setup of test_root ________\n"
"file $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/b/test_error.py, line 1\n"
"  def test_root(db):  # no db here, will error out\n"
"        fixture 'db' not found\n"
"        available fixtures: tmpdir_factory, cache, tmpdir, pytestconfig, "
"recwarn, monkeypatch, capfd, record_xml_property, capsys\n"
"        use 'py.test --fixtures [testpath]' for help on them.\n"
"\n"
"$REGENDOC_TMPDIR/b/test_error.py:1\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ TestUserHandling.test_modification ________\n"
"\n"
"self = <test_step.TestUserHandling object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_modification(self):\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_step.py:9: AssertionError\n"
"_______ test_a1 ________\n"
"\n"
"db = <conftest.DB object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_a1(db):\n"
">       assert 0, db  # to show value\n"
"E       AssertionError: <conftest.DB object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"a/test_db.py:2: AssertionError\n"
"_______ test_a2 ________\n"
"\n"
"db = <conftest.DB object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_a2(db):\n"
">       assert 0, db  # to show value\n"
"E       AssertionError: <conftest.DB object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"a/test_db2.py:2: AssertionError\n"
"======= 3 failed, 2 passed, 1 xfailed, 1 error in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:550
msgid ""
"The two test modules in the ``a`` directory see the same ``db`` fixture "
"instance while the one test in the sister-directory ``b`` doesn't see it.  "
"We could of course also define a ``db`` fixture in that sister directory's "
"``conftest.py`` file. Note that each fixture is only instantiated if there "
"is a test actually needing it (unless you use \"autouse\" fixture which are "
"always executed ahead of the first test executing)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:559
msgid "post-process test reports / failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:561
msgid ""
"If you want to postprocess test reports and need access to the executing "
"environment you can implement a hook that gets called when the test "
"\"report\" object is about to be created.  Here we write out all failing "
"test calls and also access a fixture (if it was used by the test) in case "
"you want to query/look at it during your post processing.  In our case we "
"just write some informations out to a ``failures`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:568
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"import os.path\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.hookimpl(tryfirst=True, hookwrapper=True)\n"
"def pytest_runtest_makereport(item, call):\n"
"    # execute all other hooks to obtain the report object\n"
"    outcome = yield\n"
"    rep = outcome.get_result()\n"
"\n"
"    # we only look at actual failing test calls, not setup/teardown\n"
"    if rep.when == \"call\" and rep.failed:\n"
"        mode = \"a\" if os.path.exists(\"failures\") else \"w\"\n"
"        with open(\"failures\", mode) as f:\n"
"            # let's also access a fixture for the fun of it\n"
"            if \"tmpdir\" in item.fixturenames:\n"
"                extra = \" (%s)\" % item.funcargs[\"tmpdir\"]\n"
"            else:\n"
"                extra = \"\"\n"
"\n"
"            f.write(rep.nodeid + extra + \"\\n\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:594
#: ../../../doc/en/example/simple.rst:678
msgid "if you then have failing tests:"
